      <para id="para-00069">Let’s review Figure 11.13 again. Now let’s determine which color would be selected based on these results using the ranked-choice method.</para>
      </problem>
      <solution id="sol-00006">
      <para id="para-00070">Step 1 — Determine if any candidate received a majority. There were 21 ballots. Fifty percent of 21is <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mrow><mn>0.50</mn><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mn>21</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>10.5</mn></mrow></math>. A majority is 11.</para>
      <para id="para-00071" xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml">Step 2 — Count the number of first place votes for each candidate. If a candidate has a majority, that candidate wins the election. Otherwise, eliminate the candidate(s) with the fewest votes.</para>
